06521nam a22008655i 9780814789681DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147896817 a10.18574/nyu/9780814789681.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547732  a(OCoLC)782878102  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a940.53/181442211 aBazyler, Michael J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHolocaust Justice :bThe Battle for Restitution in America's Courts /cMichael J. Bazyler. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- t1. Suing the Swiss Banks -- t2. German Industry and Its Slaves -- t3. Reclaiming Prewar Insurance Policies -- t4. Confronting the French Banks -- t5. Litigating Holocaust Looted Art -- t6. Litigating Holocaust Looted Art -- t7. The Legacy and Consequences of Holocaust Restitution -- t8. The Post–Holocaust Restitution Era -- tNotes -- tRelevant Web Sites -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Holocaust was not only the greatest murder in history; it was also the greatest theft. Historians estimate that the Nazis stole roughly $230 billion to $320 billion in assets (figured in today’s dollars), from the Jews of Europe. Since the revelations concerning the wartime activities of the Swiss banks first broke in the late 1990s, an ever-widening circle of complicity and wrongdoing against Jews and other victims has emerged in the course of lawsuits waged by American lawyers. These suits involved German corporations, French and Austrian banks, European insurance companies, and double thefts of art-first by the Nazis, and then by museums and private collectors refusing to give them up. All of these injustices have come to light thanks to the American legal system.Holocaust Justice is the first book to tell the complete story of the legal campaign, conducted mainly on American soil, to address these injustices. Michael Bazyler, a legal scholar specializing in human rights and international law, takes an in-depth look at the series of lawsuits that gave rise to a coherent campaign to right historical wrongs. Diplomacy, individual pleas for justice by Holocaust survivors and various Jewish organizations for the last fifty years, and even suits in foreign courts, had not worked. It was only with the intervention of the American courts that elderly Holocaust survivors and millions of other wartime victims throughout the world were awarded compensation, and equally important, acknowledgment of the crimes committed against them. The unique features of the American system of justice-which allowed it to handle claims that originated over fifty years ago and in another part of the world-made it the only forum in the world where Holocaust claims could be heard. Without the lawsuits brought by American lawyers, Bazyler asserts, the claims of the elderly survivors and their heirs would continue to be ignored.For the first time in history, European and even American corporations are now being forced to pay restitution for war crimes totaling billions of dollars to Holocaust survivors and other victims. Bazyler deftly tells the unfolding stories: the Swiss banks’ attempt to hide dormant bank accounts belonging to Holocaust survivors or heirs of those who perished in the war; German private companies that used slave laborers during World War II-including American subsidiaries in Germany; Italian, Swiss and German insurance companies that refused to pay on prewar policies; and the legal wrangle going on today in American courts over art looted by the Nazis in wartime Europe. He describes both the human and legal dramas involved in the struggle for restitution, bringing the often-forgotten voices of Holocaust survivors to the forefront. He also addresses the controversial legal and moral issues over Holocaust restitution and the ethical debates over the distribution of funds.With an eye to the future, Bazyler discusses the enduring legacy of Holocaust restitution litigation, which is already being used as a model for obtaining justice for historical wrongs on both the domestic and international stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHolocaust survivorsxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xReparations. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xClaims. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aHolocaust.  aaddress.  abook.  acampaign.  acomplete.  aconducted.  afaced.  afirst.  ainjustices.  alegal.  amainly.  asoil.  astory.  asurvivors.  atell.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479903140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814789681.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814789681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814789681/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK